My aunt has passed away after several health struggles. She will always be my aunt and not an \"X-aunt\". She was a loving aunt who you didn't have to see because you could hear her voice getting after her children, grandchildren out of love or just laughing from enjoying life but you never had to ask if she was there at an event. She always had a glowing face with a beautiful smile that made you feel warmth inside of her circle. She was a matriarch that embodied the Taylor + Frazier + Jessie BIG family. She and the family were always at church during the holidays and covered three or four row of pews. The family would make camps at every large sports events in town and out of town. This is another elder who shaped our American Indian Dallas community and provided a legacy to her future generations to know American Indians and how important family is today and in the future! Please send your prayers to her family members. from Brian Larney and Peggy Larney Chair and Founder of The song also won Grammy Award in the category ‘Best Song Written for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media’. Besides singing hundreds of songs in South Indian languages, he has also sung in Hindi films such as Cheeni Kum, Yuvraaj, Swades, Blue, Kaal, Lakshya, Matrubhoomi, Tere Naam, Raavan, Force, and a few others. Today Vijay Prakash is one of the most respected and sought after singers in southern India in all four languages, having sung and won innumerable awards in Tamil, Telugu, Kannada, and Malayalam films. ***Anuradha Palakurthi* **widely known as the Nightingale of New England has been recognized as the top-rated singer of Indian origin by industry legends. She has performed live with Bollywood singers like Kumar Sanu, Suresh Wadkar, Deepak Pandit, and Bappi Lahiri across the United States. Anuradha has recorded a duet with Hariharan for Ekal Vidyalaya – composed by guitarist Prasanna with drummer Sivamani, and a group of 14 multiple-Grammy winning musicians from across the globe. She sings in six Indian languages and has recorded playback for South Indian films. Earlier this year, Ms. Palakurthi’s “Jaan Meri” song from her Jaan Meri album won the prestigious Independent Music Category’s Best Song of the Year Award at the Radio Mirchi Music Awards, the Indian equivalent of the Grammys. This virtual One India Concert will feature songs from all regions of India in many different languages and will be one of its 03:05:07","updated":"2022-01-06 20:45:30","type":"photo","message":"The Strength of Our People is in Our Voice! We are handing out face covering masks with 2020 Census from the City of Dallas and Census from the American Indians and Alaska Natives Census department information to make sure you can make a difference. We will provide a drive thru setup at the Dallas Indian United Methodist Church along with the assistance of the Intertribal Community Council of Texas who are also providing traditional Mini American Indian Fry bread.This is truly a community effort to make we are invested into our Dallas American Indians but also provide the right information to show our identity and become visible in the numbers. Saturday, July 25, 2020 11am-1pm 1203 Hollywood Ave Dallas, Texas DRIVE-BY Distribution of MASKS, Census 2020 and Mini-Fry Bread. (First Come-First Serve) . . . . . . . . . . . . 2020 Census Every 10 years, the federal government counts everyone who lives in the United States. Why is the 2020 Census important to us? A complete and accurate count of American Indians and Alaska Natives throughout the United States contributes to better planning and decision-making for Indian Country, and it helps determine how billions of dollars in federal funding is distributed to communities and tribes for programs and grants. Your participation in the census builds on our communities’ progress and helps shape our future for generations to come. How will we be counted? Beginning in early 2020, every household will receive a notice in the mail to complete the 2020 Census online, by phone, or by mail. Will our information be kept confidential? Yes. Your responses to the 2020 Census are confidential and protected by law. Personal information is never shared with any government agencies or law enforcement. The #2020Census determines how billions in federal funding come into our communities. Every Native household missed will cost our people thousands of dollars. The Census can be completed online, by phone, or by mail. It takes less than ten minutes to define the next ten years. Visit https://2020census.gov/ to be counted today. We are #StatisticallySignificant. . . . . . . . . . . . . Indian Country Demographics According to the 2010 Decennial Census, 0.9% of the U.S. population, or 2.9 million people, identified as American Indian or Alaska Native alone, while 1.7% of the U.S. population, or 5.2 million people, identified as American Indian or Alaska Native alone or in combination with another race. This is an increase since 2000 of over 39%. With the upcoming 2020 Decennial Census, the population is expected to increase once again. Approximately 4,871,103 million American Indians and Alaska Natives are of voting age. About 29% of American Indians and Alaska Natives are under the age of 18, while 21.9% of the total U.S. population is under the age of 18. The median age on is 29, while the median age for the total U.S. population is 38. According to the Census Bureau 2018 Population Estimates, the states with the highest proportion of American Indians and Alaska Natives are: Alaska (27.9%), Oklahoma (17.4%), New Mexico (14.5%), South Dakota (12%), and Montana (9.2%). By 2060, the projected U.S. American Indian and Alaska Native population is estimated to reach 10 million people, or approximately 2.4% of the U.S. population. Source: National Congress of American Indians . . . . . . . . . . . . Our first one in this series is about the Indian American perspectives on the upcoming US general elections.** Not in too distant past we spoke about the transformation in movements and mind set when you stand **“for”, what you believe in and not what you are “against”** . We could dig into history of Indian freedom movement and it’s change in pace when the vision become “for” India and not necessarily just “against” British. We could also look back to Civil Right movement and establishment of “for’ vision and not “against” something. Just hearing in and around the community, and during this election cycle, we are hearing a lot of **“against” Trump & “against” Biden** movement. Isn’t it time we learn from history and start focusing on **“for” Trump and “for” Biden**? Just one such example and a topic which is running on top of Indian Americans minds lately. Nik Nikam #Right_talk - A conservative Voice and Choice What has Joe Biden done in 40 years of his political career? You are welcome to debate on the issues, but please do mind you language! Under President Trump’s leadership, Congress passed historic tax cuts and relief for hard-working Americans. The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act: Is the first major tax reform signed in 30 years. Provided tax relief for 82% of middle-class families. Doubled the Child Tax Credit proving an additional $1,000 per child in tax relief for working parents. Nearly doubled the standard deduction, a change that simplified the tax filing process for millions of Americans. Cut taxes for small business by 20%, providing $415 billion in tax relief for small business owners. Alleviated the tax burden on over 500 companies. who used those savings to fund bonuses, wage increases for 4.8 million workers. Spurred new investments into the American economy, after it was passed businesses invested $482 billion into new American projects. Repealed Obamacare’s burdensome individual mandate. Made U.S. companies competitive on the world stage, lowering the corporate tax rate from one of the highest in the industrialized world (35%) to 21%. U.S. Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth has soared under President Trump, topping 3% in 4 quarters under his administration. 2018 annual GDP growth was 2.9% In the first quarter of 2019 GDP growth was 3.1% President Trump is unleashing economic growth and jobs. Since his election, the Trump administration’s pro-growth policies have generated 6 million new jobs, the unemployment rate has fallen to its lowest point in 50 years, and wages have grown at more than 3% for 10 months in a row. The manufacturing industry created nearly half a million new jobs. 625,000 new construction jobs have been created since President Trump took office. Hispanic, Asian and African American unemployment rates have all reached record lows under President Trump. President Trump signed an executive order that expanded federally funded apprenticeship programs and on-the-job training, to provide an alternative for those looking to gain in demand skills that lack the resources to attend four year universities. The executive order set in motion a new process that makes it easier for businesses to create and scale apprenticeship programs, providing many more Americans access to an affordable education that leads to a well-paying job. The Workforce Development Advisory Council established by President Trump’s executive order has already created on-the-job training opportunities for 6.5 million Americans. The Trump administration prioritized the economic empowerment of women at home and across the globe. The Trump Administration launched the Women’s Global Development and Prosperity (W-GDP) Initiative, the first-ever whole-of-government approach focused on advancing women’s full and free participation in the global economy and allocated $50 million for the fund. Please join us in wishing her a speedy recovery! “I pray we will have a vaccine for this dreaded virus soon” By Nivedita Rath Garabadu I have been a social worker by profession from 1989, and a resident of Atlanta since 1991. My work is not very glamorous, but each time I make a difference in someone’s life, it is rewarding and fulfilling. Like everyone else, I too was looking forward to the year 2020. Then, the beginning of the new year bought news of the death of a dear friend. It was shocking, to say the least. It felt like a bad dream. Shortly thereafter, came the Coronavirus. I work as a Discharge Planner in a rehabilitation center where people with elective surgeries come for short-term rehabilitation. They get physical, occupational or speech therapy and, hopefully, are sent home after a brief stay. However, the advent of COVID-19 has made things very different at our center. When the first case of COVID-19 hit our facility, we were very transparent with all our residents and informed them that we had a case of the virus in our building. The responses came swiftly, as panic, anger, and helplessness set in. There were how’s and why’s and questions about what we were doing to keep everyone safe. There was a massive exodus from the building. Then, more testing took place and more cases were identified. We set up a “COVID Wall” where we housed our patients who had tested positive. Things were beginning to look grim. However, within a few weeks, we saw signs that made us more optimistic. People got better and, slowly but surely, we got back down to zero cases. The “Wall” went down amidst cheers from the staff. Our troubles seemed to have been short-lived! But our celebrations did not last long. Soon, our staff started falling sick and the residents started becoming ill too. Now, we are back in the situation we had so recently clawed our way out of. In these trying times, the word, \"positive\" has a different connotation. During this spike in our COVID cases, I have been around so many sweet souls who have tested “positive”. I was tested this past week and am thankfully negative, though I don’t know for how long. Trying to stay upbeat has been hard. It is heart-wrenching to see the families of our residents having to be satisfied by \"window-visits\" or zoom calls with their loved ones. No hugs or kisses, which convey so much! Recently, I was helping a \"positive” resident do a zoom call with her son. She said she wanted to go to Yellowstone National Park in October, if she is still around. My heart just melted, and I wanted to hug her so bad. There are so many such stories that tug at my heartstrings. A wife of a resident sobbed over the phone, asking me about her husband who had recently been diagnosed with the virus, “will he die?” What do I say? I pray we will have a vaccine for this dreaded virus soon, and all this will end. As the Urdu poet Mirza Ghalib once said, “Guzar jayega ye daur bhi Ghalib, zara itminan to rakh. Jab khushi na thehri to gham ki kya auqaat hai...” (Have patience Ghalib, these trying times too shall end. If joy wasn’t able to stick around, how would sorrow dare to do so…) -Coordinated by Navami Naik What's your lockdown story? Submit to of Atlanta’ is our attempt at building an archive of local Indian-American stories, one story at a time.","pageCreatedDate":"2015-08-06 01:12:59","pageCategory":"COMMUNITY","verified":false},"languageCode":"en","legacyId":0,"id":"5936358|2486463734983328"},{"platformId":"1470762849886760_2481961312100237","platform":"Facebook","date":"2020-07-17 12:48:12","updated":"2021-09-18 17:56:36","type":"photo","message":"“I am ready to meet Fall 2020 head on” BY ANURADHA GHOSH I am a Special Education teacher and mother to two girls aged ten and five. This year began like any other. Coming off the high of Christmas and winter break, we were back at school and hurtling full tilt ahead to Spring break. And then mid-March came, and with it the alarming threat posed by COVID-19. And before I could fully grapple the gravity of the situation, schools were closed indefinitely, learning had moved from in-person to online, and I found myself at home, juggling the academic needs of my children as well as the professional demands of my career. March 16. The first day of digital teaching and learning. I woke up as usual at 4.30 am, ready to work out, hit the shower, prepare breakfast and pack three lunches – my Monday to Friday routine for the last six years. But then I stopped myself as I realized I did not have to commute to work. It was a new normal. The first week started with a lot of moaning and groaning – some from me, mostly from my girls – as we settled into our online days. Children today are very technology savvy, so my older girl could navigate the demands of online learning largely by herself. My little one got the hang of it too, once she was shown the ropes. Now I could concentrate on my own teaching. We did art, music, P.E. all from the comfort of our living room. We did our lessons in pajamas. I taught math and reading from my study and I made countless trips to the kitchen fixing breakfast, snack 1, lunch, followed by snack 2 and 3 and finally dinner. I honestly never realized my kids could put away that much food!! Me either. The other thing that struck me during the early days of quarantine was that kids are messy and spill a lot. I was constantly picking up after them and churning out loads of laundry till I finally said, “stop, we will share the load, literally and figuratively’. Everyone got a chore schedule - tidying up, loading/unloading dishwasher, helping fold mounds of clothes, and everyone had to pitch in. Now this was life in quarantine! The early days of the quarantine were marked by a valiant effort at normalcy by me. I outlined a wake-up, dress-up, breakfast time and then we all hit the keyboards. We did this till lunch and then school was officially out for the day. The lazy pre-summer afternoons were spent outdoors biking and walking, anything that would let us breathe some fresh air and work off those quarantine pounds! Then, before we knew it, summer was upon us. With no vacation, no possible play dates and no summer camps, boredom finally set in. The whining grew louder and consistent. I would never have believed that one day the kids would actually say they missed being in school! And then just like that it stopped. Kids got to see friends, and picnic in the great outdoors – but always socially distanced and with a mask. We loaded up the car and headed to our favorite beach in Florida, isolating in a different set of four walls – but giving the kids a sense of a real summer vacation. We all came back with tans, shared laughter and memories. As a teacher and a mother, I was anxious about returning to the classroom, what with the rampant rise in COVID numbers in Georgia and the realization that those numbers were probably going to go up exponentially with the coming colder climate and flu season. I didn’t know how I was going to manage to keep myself, my own kids and those entrusted into my care for six hours every day safe and healthy. Visions of “don’t touch each other”, “put your mask on, it’s not a sling” and “wash those hands for 20 seconds” filled my waking hours. I talked to colleagues and everyone had the same fears and trepidations. I contemplated homeschooling my crew of two. I even contemplated taking a year off. My husband talked me off the ledge many an evening as I waited for the Board of Education in my county to share its plan. Finally, all was revealed – we would go virtual in Fall and the situation would be constantly monitored and reassessed if required. Phew! Now we could all breathe again. We have our work cut out for us – planning few more months of online learning. But we are teachers and we have learnt from our successes and missteps in Spring. I am ready to meet Fall 2020 head on. Bring it on! - Coordinated by Navami Naik Submit your lockdown story to Here are the guidelines for the article: 1. Choose a topic either from below or a topic of your choice that will be in the same theme of India Awareness. For example: If you feel there is a topic that interests you, which is not listed below, but would be interesting for folks to read, you are welcome to: * A Comprehensive Guide to Indian Cuisine *Indian Food - Why do some people generalize it by calling it curry or spicy? Culinary differences in Indian Food that most Americans may not be aware of*. * The Myth of Vegetarianism in India *Are all Indians vegetarian? What is the significance of not eating cows or pork or meat in general from an Indian point of view?* * A Look at India's Amazing Linguistic Diversity Why Most Indians Can Speak Multiple Languages Like a Dream? *Are you Hindi? Do you speak Hindu? Do you speak Indian? Number of Languages spoken in India? Where did you learn English?* * Religious Diversity in India - Co-existence of multi-faiths in India *Significance of the number of Gods? Elephant God, Monkey God? Awareness of the different religions practiced in India. Do you know that people from India can also be Muslim, Christian, Sikh and ….. ? Do you worship cows?* * Leaders of the 20th and 21st Century in India *Leaders in India, that have shaped India today, other than Mahatma Gandhi?* * Economic and Social Infrastructure, Growth and Diversity *Narrow lanes. Unimaginable traffic, Thousands of cuisines. Seven-star hotels. Slums next to them. Religious processions. Stunningly beautiful temples. Sweltering heat, Ice-packed Himalayas, Mind-blowing history. Over 500 languages. Yoga? How much do you want to know?* * Culture of Arranged Marriages in India - Does it still happen? *Arranged Marriage? Really? How can you marry someone without even knowing them?* * Microaggressions/Biases/Racist Connotations about Indians *Microaggressions you have faced? For e.g. You look too pretty for an Indian. Are all Indians smart? Doctors/Engineers? Demographics of Indians in the United States.* * Politics in India vs Politics in the United States *Topics could range from the constitution to the corruption in Government.* \uD83D\uDCF7 1. If you get to choose your topic, you might be able to pick a subject related to your personal experience or family history, which would give you a strong framework and a dose of perspective. However, this route means you must work to avoid bias—you may have strong opinions that could affect your conclusions - so please choose the topic very carefully. 1. Research for your Article - Even if you end up with a topic close to your heart, you should begin with research, using books and articles that will give you a full understanding of the subject. Go to the library and find background information about people, organizations, and events you intend to cover. Next, interview a few people to collect more information and quotes that give perspective on the topic. Don't be intimidated by the idea of interviewing important or newsworthy people—an interview can be as formal or informal as you want to make it, so relax and have fun with it. Find people with backgrounds in the topic and strong opinions, and carefully write down or record their responses for accuracy. Let the interviewees know that you will be quoting them. 1. Parts of the Article: 1. Title 1. Lead - The lead is the first sentence or paragraph, written to provide a preview of the entire article. It summarizes the story and includes many of the basic facts. 1. The Story - Once you’ve set the stage with a good lead, follow up with a well-written story that contains facts from your research and quotes from people you’ve interviewed. The article should not contain your opinions. Use the active voice—not passive voice—when possible, and write in clear, short, direct sentences. 1. The Sources 1. The Ending - a carefully chosen quote or summary to leave the reader with a strong sense of your story. 1. How to Enter: * Submissions will be accepted through July 26th, 2020. 15:54:51","updated":"2022-01-06 20:45:30","type":"photo","message":"The Strength of Our People is in Our Voice! We are handing out face covering masks with 2020 Census from the City of Dallas and Census from the American Indians and Alaska Natives Census department information to make sure you can make a difference. We will provide a drive thru setup at the Dallas Indian United Methodist Church along with the assistance of the Intertribal Community Council of Texas who are also providing traditional Mini American Indian Fry bread.This is truly a community effort to make we are invested into our Dallas American Indians but also provide the right information to show our identity and become visible in the numbers. Saturday, July 25, 2020 11am-1pm 1203 Hollywood Ave Dallas, Texas DRIVE-BY Distribution of MASKS, Census 2020 and Mini-Fry Bread. (First Come-First Serve) . . . . . . . . . . . . 2020 Census Every 10 years, the federal government counts everyone who lives in the United States. Why is the 2020 Census important to us? A complete and accurate count of American Indians and Alaska Natives throughout the United States contributes to better planning and decision-making for Indian Country, and it helps determine how billions of dollars in federal funding is distributed to communities and tribes for programs and grants. Your participation in the census builds on our communities’ progress and helps shape our future for generations to come. How will we be counted? Beginning in early 2020, every household will receive a notice in the mail to complete the 2020 Census online, by phone, or by mail. Will our information be kept confidential? Yes. Your responses to the 2020 Census are confidential and protected by law. Personal information is never shared with any government agencies or law enforcement. The #2020Census determines how billions in federal funding come into our communities. Every Native household missed will cost our people thousands of dollars. The Census can be completed online, by phone, or by mail. It takes less than ten minutes to define the next ten years. Visit https://2020census.gov/ to be counted today. We are #StatisticallySignificant. . . . . . . . . . . . . Indian Country Demographics* According to the 2010 Decennial Census, 0.9% of the U.S. population, or 2.9 million people, identified as American Indian or Alaska Native alone, while 1.7% of the U.S. population, or 5.2 million people, identified as American Indian or Alaska Native alone or in combination with another race. This is an increase since 2000 of over 39%. With the upcoming 2020 Decennial Census, the population is expected to increase once again. Approximately 4,871,103 million American Indians and Alaska Natives are of voting age. About 29% of American Indians and Alaska Natives are under the age of 18, while 21.9% of the total U.S. population is under the age of 18. The median age on is 29, while the median age for the total U.S. population is 38. According to the Census Bureau 2018 Population Estimates, the states with the highest proportion of American Indians and Alaska Natives are: Alaska (27.9%), Oklahoma (17.4%), New Mexico (14.5%), South Dakota (12%), and Montana (9.2%). By 2060, the projected U.S. American Indian and Alaska Native population is estimated to reach 10 million people, or approximately 2.4% of the U.S. population. *Source: National Congress of American Indians . . . . . . . . . . . . Hailed as a historic event in the annals of India, the most auspicious groundbreaking ceremony will be exhibited through images of Lord Ram and 3D portraits of the Ram Temple model on the giant billboards at Times Square. Among the prominent billboards being leased for the day is the 17000-sq-ft LED display screen for the largest outdoor display at Times Square. Indians in the US are eagerly waiting for the moment when Prime Minister Modi will break the holy ground and lay the foundation stone of the temple. Visuals of the ceremony will be beamed across billboards, from 8 AM till 10 PM on August 5, at Times Square. \n       \n“Under Prime Minister Modi, the construction of the Ram Temple is a dream come true for Hindus all over the world. Till six years back, we never thought that this day will come soon but due to Modi’s leadership, this day has come and we want to celebrate it in a befitting way,\" said Jagdish Sewhani, President of the American India Public Affairs Committee. \uD83C\uDF39गं गणपत्ये पुत्र वरदाय नमः।। इस मंत्र के जाप से उत्तम संतान कि प्राप्ति होती हैं। \uD83C\uDF39ॐ वर वरदाय विजय गणपतये नमः इस मंत्र के जाप से मुकदमे में सफलता प्राप्त होती हैं। \uD83C\uDF39ॐ
